# Personal Portfolio Landing Page
Project Requirements Document (PRD)

---

# 1. Project Overview

Build a **responsive personal portfolio landing page** that showcases a developer's:

- Introduction
- Background
- Skills
- Projects
- Certifications / Achievements
- Contact information

The website will act as a **professional digital identity** that can be shared with recruiters, collaborators, and clients.

The project must be implemented as a **static website using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript**.

---

# 2. Goals

The portfolio website should:

- Present the developer professionally
- Demonstrate frontend development skills
- Be mobile responsive
- Have clean and readable code
- Be deployable as a static website
- Follow good UI/UX practices

---

# 3. Technology Stack

## Required

- HTML5
- CSS3
- JavaScript (Vanilla)

## Optional (Not Required)

- Bootstrap
- TailwindCSS
- React
- Next.js
- Vue

For this assignment **plain HTML/CSS/JS is recommended**.

---

# 4. Project Structure

The project must follow this structure:


portfolio-website/
│
├── index.html
├── style.css
├── script.js
│
├── images/
│ └── profile.jpg (optional)
│
└── README.md


---

# 5. Website Sections (Required)

The portfolio must include the following sections **in this order**:

1. Navbar  
2. Hero Section  
3. About Section  
4. Skills Section  
5. Projects Section  
6. Certifications / Achievements  
7. Contact Section  
8. Footer  

Each section should be implemented using **semantic HTML tags** where possible.

---

# 6. Navigation Bar

## Requirements

The navigation bar should contain:

- Developer name or logo
- Navigation links to page sections

Example navigation links:


Home
About
Skills
Projects
Contact


## Behavior

- Links should scroll to the respective section
- Navigation must work on mobile devices
- Mobile view should include a **hamburger menu**

---

# 7. Hero Section

The hero section is the **first visible section**.

## Content

Include:

- Developer name
- Short professional description
- Profile image (optional)
- Call-to-action button

### Example Text


Hi, I'm John Doe
Frontend Developer passionate about building modern web applications.


### CTA Button Example


View My Work


The button should scroll to the **Projects section**.

---

# 8. About Section

This section should describe:

- Developer background
- Technologies known
- Interests in software development
- Career goals

Possible topics:

- Web Development
- Backend Development
- AI / Machine Learning
- Cloud Engineering

The content should be a **short paragraph (4–6 sentences)**.

---

# 9. Skills Section

The skills section should visually present technical skills.

Skills may be grouped into categories.

## Programming Languages

- JavaScript
- Python
- Java
- C++

## Web Technologies

- HTML
- CSS
- React
- Node.js

## Tools

- Git
- GitHub
- Docker
- VS Code

## UI Suggestions

Skills can be displayed using:

- Cards
- Icons
- Grid layout
- Progress bars

Spacing should be clean and consistent.

---

# 10. Projects Section

This section should display **2–3 projects**.

Each project must include:

- Project title
- Short description
- Technologies used
- GitHub link (if available)

### Example

**Weather App**

Description:


A web application that fetches weather data from a public weather API.


Technologies used:


JavaScript
OpenWeather API
HTML
CSS


Projects should be displayed as **cards or tiles**.

---

# 11. Certifications / Achievements

This section should include:

- Online certifications
- Hackathons
- Coding competitions
- Professional courses

### Example


AWS Cloud Practitioner
Google Data Analytics Certificate
Meta Frontend Developer Certification


Layout options:

- List
- Grid
- Cards

---

# 12. Contact Section

Provide ways for people to reach the developer.

Required contact methods:

- Email
- GitHub
- LinkedIn

Example:


Email: your@email.com

GitHub: github.com/username
LinkedIn: linkedin.com/in/username


Optional:

- Contact form

---

# 13. Footer

The footer should contain:


© 2026 Your Name
Built with HTML, CSS and JavaScript


Footer should be minimal and centered.

---

# 14. Design Requirements

## Responsive Design

The website must work on:

- Mobile devices
- Tablets
- Desktop screens

Use **CSS media queries**.

Example breakpoint:


768px


---

## Typography

Use clean and readable fonts.

Recommended fonts:

- Inter
- Poppins
- Roboto

---

## Color Scheme

Use a consistent color palette.

Example palette:


Primary: #2563eb
Background: #f8fafc
Text: #0f172a
Accent: #1e293b


---

## Layout Principles

The design should include:

- Clear spacing between sections
- Consistent margins
- Balanced layout
- Readable typography
- Clear visual hierarchy

---

# 15. JavaScript Features (Required)

At least **one interactive feature must be implemented**.

Possible features:

### Smooth Scroll Navigation

Navigation links scroll smoothly to sections.

---

### Mobile Menu Toggle

Hamburger menu opens and closes navigation links.

---

### Scroll Animations

Sections animate when entering the viewport.

---

### Contact Form Validation

Validate form inputs using JavaScript.

---

### Dark Mode Toggle

Allow switching between light and dark themes.

---

# 16. CSS Layout Techniques

The layout should use modern CSS techniques.

Recommended:

## Flexbox

Use Flexbox for:

- Navigation bar
- Skills section
- Project cards

Common properties:


display: flex
justify-content
align-items
gap
flex-direction


---

## CSS Grid (Optional)

Grid can be used for:

- Skills layout
- Project gallery

---

# 17. Code Quality Requirements

## HTML

- Use semantic tags where possible
- Maintain consistent indentation
- Use meaningful structure

Examples:

<header> <section> <footer> ```
CSS

Organize CSS logically

Use meaningful class names

Example class names:

.hero-section
.project-card
.skill-item
.contact-section
JavaScript

Use modern and readable JavaScript.

Examples:

document.querySelector()
addEventListener()
classList.toggle()

Code should be easy to understand.

18. Deployment

The website must be deployed online.

Recommended platforms:

GitHub Pages

https://pages.github.com/

Netlify

https://www.netlify.com/

Vercel

https://vercel.com/

Example live URL:

https://username.github.io/portfolio
19. Deliverables

The final submission must include:

1. GitHub Repository

Repository must contain:

Source code

README.md

Project structure

2. Live Website Link

Example:

https://username.github.io/portfolio
20. Optional Enhancements

Optional improvements include:

Dark mode

Scroll animations

Hover effects

Animated buttons

Project screenshots

These enhancements can make the portfolio more engaging.

21. Acceptance Criteria

The project will be considered complete when:

All required sections are implemented

Website is responsive

At least one JavaScript interactive feature is included

Code is clean and readable

The website is deployed online

A GitHub repository is provided

22. Estimated Time

Total expected time:

8–10 hours

Typical breakdown:

Planning: 30 minutes
HTML Structure: 2 hours
CSS Styling: 3 hours
Responsive Design: 1.5 hours
JavaScript Functionality: 1 hour
Testing: 30 minutes
Deployment: 30 minutes